Build ID: Eclipse 3.2.1 build M20060921-0945

Steps To Reproduce: see below

More information:
[ Eclipse SDK, Version: 3.2.1 Build id: M20060921-0945           ]
[              org.eclipse.ui.workbench_3.2.1.M20060906-0800.jar ]
[ running on Windows XP with SP2                                 ]

Since Eclipse 3.2, it is possible to change UI of workbench including Coolbar 
by creating a subclass of WorkbenchPresentationFactory also implementing 
IActionBarPresentationFactory.

I know how to call 

    ActionContributionItem#setMode(ActionContributionItem.MODE_FORCE_TEXT)

to enable caption of toolbar buttons on coolbar. By default workbench shows
caption text on the right side of icon (seeing attached screenshot).

But after providing an IActionBarPresentationFactory implementation with code
as below:

    public IToolBarManager2 createToolBarManager() {
        return new ToolBarManager2(SWT.FLAT | SWT.BOTTOM);
    }

now both icon and caption of toolbar buttons disappeared.

Debugging into deep codes of ToolItem, I found that in this case ToolItem 
holding text of null (accessible via setText(..)/getText() ). It seems to be 
a bug(?) to calculate size of toolbar buttons as zero-wide which suppressing 
toolbar buttons. I cannot figure it out from ToolItem.java instead of showing 
a work-around as below: 

    public IToolBarManager2 createToolBarManager() {
        return new MyToolBarManager2(SWT.FLAT | SWT.BOTTOM);
    }

    class MyToolBarManager2 extends ToolBarManager2{

        public MyToolBarManager2(int style) {
            super(style);
        }

        @Override
        public void update(boolean force) {
            super.update(force);
            ToolBar toolBar = this.getControl();
            if (toolBar!=null && !toolBar.isDisposed()){
                for (ToolItem item : toolBar.getItems()){
                    Object data = item.getData();
                    if (data instanceof ActionContributionItem){
                        ActionContributionItem ci = (ActionContributionItem) data;
                        if (ci.getAction()!=null){
                            item.setText(ci.getAction().getText());
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }

    }

Adding Michael's explenation:
[Browser] browserSupport.createBrowser(ID) does't open browser in the same 
window, when using the same ID
The problem is in constructor of DefaultBrowserSupport:

BrowserManager.getInstance().addObserver(new Observer() {
  public void update(Observable o, Object arg) {
    .....
    browserIdMap.clear();
  }
});

browserIdMap is cleared, when preference change event is being received (the 
preference change is on browser recent pages).

