More information:

The problem is in the newest BIRT version. We use the BIRT with Tomcat
as a webapplication. When one of the parameters contains a special character
the function ParameterAccessor.toISOString is called with this parameter
encoded in UTF-8.
Please take a look at this function in the latest version from the 
repository (Version 1.81).

Here is some sample code to debug what the function does:

public static void main(String[] args) {
	byte[] ba = {new Integer(0xC3).byteValue(), new Integer(0xB6).byteValue()};

	try {
		String theUTFString = new String (ba, "UTF-8");
		String notTheExpectedIsoString = new String (theUTFString.getBytes("UTF-8"), "ISO-8859-1");
		byte[] isoByteArray = notTheExpectedIsoString.getBytes("ISO-8859-1");
	}
	catch (UnsupportedEncodingException e) {
		System.err.println (e.getMessage());
	}
}

The function is called with a UTF-8 encoded string. In the sample it is
constructed from the byte array containing C3 B6 which is '' in UTF-8 encoding.
In debug mode you can verify that the string is ''. Calling the String
constructor like it is done in the function toISOString is done in the next
line. (Get the bytes as UTF-8 and construct a new string as ISO-8859-1).
Take a look at the constructed string in debug mode. It is NOT the string in
ISO-8859-1 but exactly the same byte sequence as before!

Please try the sample code and take a look at the class ParameterAccessor.
The function toISOString is called when parameters with special characters
are passed via the URL. 
Again: this function does not convert a string from UTF-8 to ISO-8859-1! 
The byte representation stays the same and this is what you will see when you 
evaluate the parameter value in a report.

